fourth, social mobilization, draws on utopianism, anarchism, historical materialism, and other radical thought and looks to the structural transformation of society "from below." After developing a basic vocabulary in Part One, the author proceeds in Part Two to a critical history of each of the four planning traditions. The story begins with the prophetic visions of Saint-Simon and assesses the contributions of such diverse thinkers as Comte, Marx, Dewey, Mannheim, Tugwell, Mumford, Simon, and Habermas. It is carried forward in Part Three by Friedmann's own nontechnocratic, dialectical approach to planning as a method for recovering political community.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 27. Jan 2023) 0aPlanningxHistory. 0aPolitical planningxHistory. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / Public Affairs & Administration.2bisacsh  aBentham, Jeremy.  aComintern.  aGerman Historical School.  aHitler-Stalin pact.  aJames, William.  aJeffersonian democrat.  aKeynesian economics.  aLaw of Three Stages.  aMao Tse-tung.  aMarxists.  aNew Harmony.  aPareto optimum.  aaction.  aartificial intelligence.  abureaucracy.  acalculation.  acapital restructuring.  acollective self-reliance.  acritical theory.  adialogue.  aengineering.  afederalism.  afeminism.  ahistorical materialism.  ahumanistic psychologies.  aimplementation.  aindustrialism.  aknowledge.  alife space.  apolitical community.  arationality.  asocial anarchism.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertPrinceton University Press eBook-Package Archive 1927-1999z978311044249608iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertPrinceton University Press eBook-Package Gap Yearsz978311078423740uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780691214009?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780691214009423Coveruhttps://www.degruy